
[1]immerse

   IMMERSE, v.t. immers'. [L. immersus, from immergo; in and mergo, to
   plunge.]

   1. To put under water or other fluid; to plunge; to dip.

   2. To sink or cover deep; to cover wholly; as, to be immersed in a
   wood.

   3. To plunge; to overwhelm; to involve; to engage deeply; as, to
   immerse in business or cares.

   It is impossible for a man to have a lively hope in another life,and
   yet be deeply immersed in the enjoyment of this.
